'''William Craig Zwick''' (born June 10, 1947) has been a [[general authority]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) since 1995.  

==LDS Church service==
Zwick was born in Salt Lake City, Utah.  He served as a [[Mormon missionary|missionary]] for the LDS Church in [[Argentina]]. [[Richard G. Scott]] of the [[Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|Quorum of the Twelve]] was one of Zwick's [[mission president]]s. While serving on this mission he worked on his first LDS Church chapel construction project.<ref name = ensign>[http://www.lds.org/ensign/1995/05/news-of-the-church/elder-w-craig-zwick-of-the-seventy <U+201C>Elder W. Craig Zwick of the Seventy,<U+201D>] ''[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]'', May 1995, p. 107</ref> Prior to his call as a general authority, Zwick served as [[Mission president|president]] of the church's [[Chile]] [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]] South [[Mission (LDS Church)|Mission]].<ref>''2008 Deseret Morning News Church Almanac'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Deseret Morning News, 2007), p. 53.</ref>  Since becoming a general authority, he has served as president of the church's Brazil, Brazil South, and North America Northeast [[Area (LDS Church)|areas]]. He has also served in the presidencies of the Europe West and Europe Central areas. In 2011, he was appointed an Assistant Executive Director of both the church's Missionary and Correlation departments. In May 2014, he began service as president of the [[Puerto Rico]] [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] Mission.<ref>[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865602185/New-mission-presidents.html "New mission presidents"], ''[[Church News]]'', 2014-05-03.</ref>

==Career==
Zwick received a degree in business management and finance from the [[University of Utah]].

Zwick started working for his father's construction company, Zwick Construction Inc. and eventually became the owner and operator. They built many hospitals and schools.  The company also frequently performed construction jobs for the LDS Church. These projects included the [[Family History Library]], the South Visitors Center on [[Temple Square]], the [[Museum of Church History and Art]],<ref name = ensign/> and the [[Portland Oregon Temple]].<ref>''2008 Deseret Morning News Church Almanac'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Deseret Morning News, 2007) p. 554.</ref> He also worked for three years as executive director of the [[Utah Department of Transportation]].  

==Family==
Zwick married Janet Johnson and they are the parents of four children.

One of his children, Spencer, served with [[Mitt Romney]] in Massachusetts and then on [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|Romney's 2012 presidential campaign]] as national finance chair.<ref name=NYT01>[[Jim Rutenberg|Rutenberg, Jim]], [http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/17/us/politics/support-for-romney-by-old-mormon-families.html?pagewanted=3&_r=1&hp "Mormons<U+2019> First Families Rally Behind Romney"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', pp. 1 & 3, July 16, 2012. Retrieved 2012-07-17.</ref>

In an interview, Zwick said his maternal ancestors go <U+201C>back in church history to [[Hyrum Smith|Hyrum]]<U+201D> (Smith).<ref name=NYT01/>

